{"isSidechain":true,"agentId":"579f64e5-ec19-481","type":"toolResult","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"functions.read:64","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"package tests\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\n\t\"github.com/google/uuid\"\n)\n\ntype GenSequentialUUID struct {\n\tsequences map[string]int\n}\n\n// Generates a predictable (sequential) UUID that starts with a ns.\n// N.B., ns must only contain UUID-friendly chars: [0-9a-fA-F]\nfunc (u *GenSequentialUUID) GenNamespacedUUID(namespace string) uuid.UUID {\n\tif u.sequences == nil {\n\t\tu.sequences = make(map[string]int)\n\t}\n\n\tfor len(namespace) < 8 {\n\t\tnamespace += \"0\"\n\t}\n\tif len(namespace) > 8 {\n\t\tnamespace = namespace[:8]\n\t}\n\tseqNum := u.sequences[namespace]\n\tseqNum++\n\tu.sequences[namespace] = seqNum\n\n\treturn uuid.MustParse(fmt.Sprintf(\"%s-0000-0000-0000-%012d\", namespace, seqNum))\n}\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1780920038479},"timestamp":"2026-06-08T12:00:38.482Z","cwd":"/Users/laimonasrastenis/Projects/kubecast"}
{"isSidechain":true,"agentId":"579f64e5-ec19-481","type":"assistant","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"    Now I have enough understanding to write the tests. Let me focus on what's needed:\n\n1. **Handler tests** - Add to `handler_test.go`:\n   - Test that failVariant produces descriptive error message\n   - Test that VariantType is included in signals\n\n2. **Production simulator tests** - Create `production_simulator_test.go`:\n   - Test that loadContextWithFallback tries older snapshots for full_cluster\n   - Test that no fallback happens for rebalancing_plan or snapshot types\n\n3. **Workflow test** - Create `analysis_workflow_test.go`:\n   - Test that baseline failure causes workflow to fail analysis\n   - Test that FinalizeAnalysis propagates error\n\n4. **Snapshot service test** for GetRecentSnapshotLocations\n\nLet me start by writing the handler tests, then the simulator tests, then the workflow test.\n\nFor the handler tests, I'll test:\n- `signalFromVariant` includes VariantType\n- `failVariant` includes VariantType in signal\n- `failVariant` includes descriptive error message\n\nFor the simulator tests, I need:\n- Mock debug.Service \n- Mock snapshots.Service\n- Test loadSourcePlan for full_cluster (SourcePlanID==nil, SnapshotAnchorTime==nil)\n- Test loadContextWithFallback behavior\n\nActually, looking at `production_simulator.go` again, `loadContextWithFallback` is the function to test. It's a private method but I can test it through `RunVariant`. But `RunVariant` also calls `loadSourcePlan` and `snapshotService.GetSnapshot` and `runtime.RunSimulation`, which makes it harder to test in isolation.\n\nLet me think about whether I should test `RunVariant` end-to-end or just `loadContextWithFallback` directly. Since `loadContextWithFallback` is a private method on `productionSimulator`, I can't call it directly from the test package. I have a few options:\n\n1. Make `loadContextWithFallback` a public method on an interface\n2. Test through `RunVariant` with mocks\n\nFor option 2, I need the simulator to actually work, which means I need:\n- debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot to work \n- snapshotService.GetSnapshot to work\n- runtime.RunSimulation to work\n\nThis is complex. Let me think about what the test should actually verify.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow in `RunVariant`:\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) RunVariant(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, mutations []mutation.Mutation) (*executortypes.SimulationResult, string, error) {\n    sourcePlan, err := s.loadSourcePlan(ctx, req)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, \"\", err\n    }\n    snapshotLocation := sourcePlan.SnapshotLocation\n\n    clusterContext, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan cluster context: %w\", err)\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nSo if I mock `snapshotService.GetLatestSnapshot` (for full_cluster path), `debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot` (to return metadata error), and `snapshotService.GetRecentSnapshotLocations` (to return fallback locations), then `loadContextWithFallback` will actually try fallback snapshots. Then `debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot` on the fallback location will return a context, and then `snapshotService.GetSnapshot` needs to return a snapshot, then `runtime.RunSimulation` needs to return a result.\n\nThis is doable but requires a lot of mocks. Let me think if there's a simpler way.\n\nActually, I could test through `RunVariant` by:\n1. Mock `snapshotService.GetLatestSnapshot` to return a snapshot with a location\n2. Mock `debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot` to first return `ErrMetadataMissing`, then return a cluster context on subsequent calls\n3. Mock `snapshotService.GetRecentSnapshotLocations` to return the same location\n4. Mock `snapshotService.GetSnapshot` to return a snapshot\n5. Mock `runtime.RunSimulation` to return a result\n\nActually, wait. Looking at the code:\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) loadContextWithFallback(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, snapshotLocation string) (*debug.ClusterContext, error) {\n\tclusterContext, err := s.debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(ctx, snapshotLocation)\n\tif err == nil {\n\t\treturn clusterContext, nil\n\t}\n\n\t// Only attempt snapshot fallback for full_cluster trigger type (no source plan, no time anchor).\n\tif req.SourcePlanID != nil || req.SnapshotAnchorTime != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\n\t// Check if the error is due to missing metadata (the signal to try older snapshots).\n\tif !errors.Is(err, debug.ErrMetadataMissing) {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\n\trecentLocations, listErr := s.snapshotService.GetRecentSnapshotLocations(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotFallbackMaxAge)\n\tif listErr != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\n\tfor _, loc := range recentLocations {\n\t\tif loc == snapshotLocation {\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\t\tfallbackContext, fallbackErr := s.debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(ctx, loc)\n\t\tif fallbackErr == nil {\n\t\t\treturn fallbackContext, nil\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\n\treturn nil, err\n}\n```\n\nThe issue is that `loadSourcePlan` already calls `GetLatestSnapshot` which returns a snapshot location. Then `loadContextWithFallback` receives this location and tries to load context from it. If it fails with metadata error, it tries `GetRecentSnapshotLocations` which should return *other* locations.\n\nWait, but `GetRecentSnapshotLocations` returns locations within the last 5 minutes, and the latest snapshot is included. So when iterating, it skips the current one.\n\nFor testing, I could have:\n1. `GetLatestSnapshot` returns location \"loc1\"\n2. `LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(\"loc1\")` returns `ErrMetadataMissing`\n3. `GetRecentSnapshotLocations` returns `[\"loc1\", \"loc2\", \"loc3\"]`\n4. `LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(\"loc2\")` returns a valid context\n\nBut wait, there are 2 issues:\n1. In `RunVariant`, after getting the context, it also calls `snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)`. But `snapshotLocation` is still \"loc1\" (from sourcePlan). Shouldn't it use the fallback location? Let me re-check the code.\n\nLooking at `RunVariant`:\n```go\nclusterContext, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\n```\n\nBut `snapshotLocation` isn't updated to the fallback location! That's a bug. The `loadContextWithFallback` returns a `*debug.ClusterContext` but the `snapshotLocation` passed to `RunVariant` is still the original sourcePlan location.\n\nWait, looking at the code more carefully:\n```go\nclusterContext, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan cluster context: %w\", err)\n}\nmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\nsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)\n```\n\nSo `snapshotLocation` is still the original location from sourcePlan. But the cluster context was loaded from a different snapshot (the fallback). This seems like a bug - if we load context from fallback location \"loc2\", shouldn't we also load the snapshot from \"loc2\"?\n\nHmm, but looking at the `ClusterContext`, it includes `ModelDependencies` which has a `Snapshot` field. Let me re-read the code:\n\n```go\nclusterContext, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan cluster context: %w\", err)\n}\nmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\nsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)\n```\n\nAfter getting the cluster context, it extracts `md.Snapshot` from the cluster context. Then it tries to load the snapshot from `snapshotLocation` (which is still the original). But then:\n\n```go\nmd.Snapshot = snap\ninput := &mutation.SimulationInput{\n    Snapshot:       md.Snapshot,\n    ClusterContext: clusterContext,\n}\n```\n\nIt overwrites `md.Snapshot` with `snap`. So even though the cluster context was loaded from \"loc2\", the snapshot used for simulation is still from \"loc1\". This is actually problematic because the debug context and snapshot might be from different times...\n\nActually wait, let me re-read. The `clusterContext` is a `*debug.ClusterContext` which has a `ModelDependencies` field. The `md` is `clusterContext.ModelDependencies`. Then `snap` is loaded from `snapshotLocation` and assigned to `md.Snapshot`. The `input` uses `md.Snapshot` which is now the snap from `snapshotLocation`.\n\nSo if the purpose of snapshot fallback is to find a snapshot with valid metadata, and we find that in \"loc2\", then shouldn't we also use \"loc2\" for loading the snapshot? Actually, looking at it more carefully - the debug context location is metadata on the snapshot object. If the snapshot at \"loc1\" exists but doesn't have the context metadata, then the fallback finds \"loc2\" which does have context metadata. For the simulation, we need both the snapshot data AND the debug context. The snapshot data is at \"loc1\", the debug context is at \"loc2\".\n\nActually I think the intent might be different. Looking at what `LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot` does:\n1. Parse the snapshot location\n2. Get the debug context location from snapshot metadata\n3. Load the cluster context from the debug context location\n\nSo if step 2 fails because metadata is missing, the snapshot itself exists but the metadata pointing to the debug context is missing. The fallback looks for older snapshots that have the metadata. Once found, it loads the debug context from that older snapshot's metadata. But then it still loads the *snapshot data* from the original location. This means we'd be simulating with a more recent snapshot but using an older debug context. That seems wrong.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read. The code says:\n```go\nclusterContext, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\n```\n\nAfter this, `snapshotLocation` is unchanged. If `loadContextWithFallback` finds \"loc2\" as having valid metadata, it loads the cluster context from loc2's metadata. But then for simulation, we use the original snapshot from loc1. This seems like a bug in the implementation - we should probably update `snapshotLocation` to the fallback location too.\n\nHmm, but the spec says \"the system tries progressively older snapshots (up to 5 minutes old) and uses the first one with valid metadata\". It doesn't say we also switch the snapshot. But in practice, the debug context and snapshot are tightly coupled - you need a debug context that matches the snapshot. If the latest snapshot is missing metadata, using an older debug context with the newer snapshot might give inconsistent results.\n\nLet me re-read the spec more carefully:\n> For full_cluster trigger type, when the latest snapshot lacks context metadata, the system tries progressively older snapshots (up to 5 minutes old) and uses the first one with valid metadata.\n\n\"uses the first one with valid metadata\" - this sounds like it should use the older snapshot entirely, not just its metadata. So the `snapshotLocation` should be updated to the fallback location.\n\nBut the current implementation doesn't update `snapshotLocation`. This means `RunVariant` returns the original `snapshotLocation` even though the context was loaded from a different location. And `snapshotService.GetSnapshot` is called with the original location.\n\nI think this is an incomplete implementation from the previous agent. Let me fix this.\n\nActually wait, looking at this more carefully. `loadContextWithFallback` returns only the cluster context, not the location it found. The caller needs to know which location was used. Let me modify `loadContextWithFallback` to return the location too, or update `snapshotLocation` in `RunVariant`.\n\nLooking at the current code structure:\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) loadContextWithFallback(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, snapshotLocation string) (*debug.ClusterContext, error) {\n```\n\nI can change this to return the location too:\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) loadContextWithFallback(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, snapshotLocation string) (*debug.ClusterContext, string, error) {\n```\n\nOr you can do it inline in `RunVariant`. Let me change `loadContextWithFallback` to return the effective snapshot location.\n\nActually, I think a cleaner approach is:\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) RunVariant(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, mutations []mutation.Mutation) (*executortypes.SimulationResult, string, error) {\n    ...\n    sourcePlan, err := s.loadSourcePlan(ctx, req)\n    ...\n    clusterContext, effectiveLocation, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\n    ...\n    snap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, effectiveLocation)\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nBut wait, I need to check how the snapshot service stores things. Is the debug context bundled with the snapshot? Or are they separate files? Looking at the debug service:\n- `LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot` reads the snapshot metadata to find the debug context location, then loads the debug context.\n- The `clusterContext` contains `ModelDependencies` which doesn't include the snapshot itself.\n\nWhen you call `RunVariant`, after getting the cluster context:\n```go\nmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\nsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan snapshot: %w\", err)\n}\nmd.Snapshot = snap\n```\n\nSo yes, the snapshot is loaded separately from the cluster context. This would mean if we load cluster context from loc2's metadata but then load the snapshot from loc1, we're mixing them.\n\nI think the correct approach is:\n1. `loadContextWithFallback` should return the effective location\n2. `RunVariant` should use the effective location for both cluster context and snapshot loading\n3. The snapshot location returned by `RunVariant` should be the effective location\n\nLet me check if this is what the spec intends. The spec says: \"uses the first one with valid metadata\" - meaning the older snapshot itself.\n\nWait, actually I should re-read the implementation more carefully:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) loadContextWithFallback(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, snapshotLocation string) (*debug.ClusterContext, error) {\n\tclusterContext, err := s.debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(ctx, snapshotLocation)\n\tif err == nil {\n\t\treturn clusterContext, nil\n\t}\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nIf the first call succeeds, it returns the clusterContext loaded from the snapshot metadata. If it fails, it tries other snapshots. If a fallback succeeds, it returns the clusterContext loaded from the fallback snapshot's metadata. But `snapshotLocation` in `RunVariant` is not updated.\n\nI think this is a genuine issue that needs to be fixed. Let me update `loadContextWithFallback` to return the effective location.\n\nHowever, looking at the test requirement: \"Test for snapshot fallback iteration logic\" - this only needs to test the iteration logic, not the full integration. The existing tests probably just need to verify that when metadata is missing, it tries older snapshots, and when it finds one, it uses that.\n\nLet me check if there's an interface-based way to test this. Actually, `loadContextWithFallback` is on `productionSimulator` which implements the `Simulator` interface. I can test through `RunVariant` by mocking all dependencies.\n\nLet me also consider whether I need to fix the incomplete implementation from the previous agent. Given:\n1. The spec says \"uses the first one with valid metadata\"\n2. The current code returns the clusterContext but doesn't update snapshotLocation\n\nI think I should fix this. Let me modify `loadContextWithFallback` to return `(*debug.ClusterContext, string, error)`.\n\nLet me do this carefully:\n```go\nfunc (s *productionSimulator) loadContextWithFallback(ctx context.Context, req mq.AnalysisVariantRequest, snapshotLocation string) (*debug.ClusterContext, string, error) {\n\tclusterContext, err := s.debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(ctx, snapshotLocation)\n\tif err == nil {\n\t\treturn clusterContext, snapshotLocation, nil\n\t}\n    ...\n    for _, loc := range recentLocations {\n        if loc == snapshotLocation {\n            continue\n        }\n        fallbackContext, fallbackErr := s.debugService.LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(ctx, loc)\n        if fallbackErr == nil {\n            return fallbackContext, loc, nil\n        }\n    }\n    return nil, snapshotLocation, err\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `RunVariant`:\n```go\nclusterContext, effectiveLocation, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan cluster context: %w\", err)\n}\nsnapshotLocation = effectiveLocation\nmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\nsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)\n...\n```\n\nThis way, when fallback succeeds, we use the fallback location for everything.\n\nWait, but there's another consideration. The `snapshotService.GetSnapshot` loads the *snapshot data* - the pods, nodes, etc. The `clusterContext` has `ModelDependencies` - the model data. Are they from the same snapshot? Let me re-read `LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot`:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *service) LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot(ctx context.Context, snapshotLocation string) (*ClusterContext, error) {\n    snapshotPath, err := s.snapshotClient.ObjectNameFromFullPath(ctx, snapshotLocation)\n    ...\n    contextLocation, err := GetRebalancerDebugContextLocationForSnapshot(ctx, s.snapshotClient, snapshotPath)\n    ...\n    return s.loadClusterContextFromLocation(ctx, contextLocation)\n}\n```\n\nSo `LoadRebalancerClusterContextForSnapshot` reads the snapshot metadata to find the debug context location, then loads the cluster context from that debug context. It does NOT read the actual snapshot data (pods, nodes, etc.).\n\nThen in `RunVariant`:\n```go\nmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\nsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)\nmd.Snapshot = snap\n```\n\nHere, `snap` is loaded from `snapshotLocation` and assigned to `md.Snapshot`. So `ClusterContext` has:\n- `ModelDependencies` (from debug context)\n- `Snapshot` (from snapshot data, loaded separately)\n\nThese need to match. If we load the debug context from \"loc2\" but the snapshot from \"loc1\", they won't match. So using `effectiveLocation` for both is correct.\n\nOK, let me fix the `loadContextWithFallback` to return the effective location, and update `RunVariant` accordingly.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-examine this. There's a subtlety. The debug context contains model dependencies that were computed when the snapshot was taken. The snapshot itself contains pods, nodes, etc. If we use a newer snapshot with an older debug context, the model dependencies might not match the actual state.\n\nSo yes, I need to fix this.\n\nLet me also check if the previous agent already started steps 6-7. I need to check the ferment state. Actually, looking at the context, the orchestrator said steps 6-7 were partially completed. Let me check if they need to be completed.\n\nSince this is a subagent, let me focus on the technical work first and let the orchestrator handle ferment step management. Let me fix the code issues I found, add all the tests, and ensure everything builds and passes.\n\nLet me first fix the `loadContextWithFallback` to return effective snapshot location.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"toolCall","id":"functions.edit:65","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/Users/laimonasrastenis/Projects/kubecast/services/autoscaler/internal/services/clusteradvisor/executor/production_simulator.go","edits":[{"oldText":"\tclusterContext, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan cluster context: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\n\tsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)","newText":"\tclusterContext, effectiveLocation, err := s.loadContextWithFallback(ctx, req, snapshotLocation)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, snapshotLocation, fmt.Errorf(\"loading source plan cluster context: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tsnapshotLocation = effectiveLocation\n\tmd := clusterContext.ModelDependencies\n\tsnap, err := s.snapshotService.GetSnapshot(ctx, req.ClusterID, snapshotLocation)"}]}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kimchi-dev","model":"kimi-k2.6","usage":{"input":54664,"output":4478,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":59142,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1780920038484,"responseId":"chatcmpl-9a1f81f254ef5728"},"timestamp":"2026-06-08T12:06:31.292Z","cwd":"/Users/laimonasrastenis/Projects/kubecast"}
